which have come down to us almost intact.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Cicero*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
It was in 67 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, four years before Cicero's <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship, that Lucius Roscius Otho, as <A CLASS="glossary" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Tribunus.html#plebis
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Glossary,WIDTH,210)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>tribune of the people, introduced his law giving the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">equites</SPAN> a special place at the spectacles, namely, the fourteen rows of seats next those of the senators. The law, however, had only recently been enacted.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: For more detailed information, see the article
		<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Leges.html#Roscia_Theatralis
		"TARGET="index"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Lex Roscia Theatralis
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
