<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Cicero*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
<I>Cf.</I> 	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/cat3.shtml#9
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cicero, <I>in Catil.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.4.9</A>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: A great number of such forgeries circulated in Antiquity, much like fake Nostradamus quatrains today. One set in particular should be mentioned, since it has come down to us, and is often confused with the Sibylline Books, which were destroyed by Stilicho. The Sibylline Oracles
	<A HREF="
https://elfinspell.com/SibyllineOraclesMyIntro.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(online in their entirety at Elfinspell)
	</A>
are among the many fevered products of late Roman Alexandria; in them Jewish and Christian authors, mixing ex post facto prophecy, numerology, apocalyptic writing and sundry mystical conceits, brought forth a work of enormous interest to the incurably credulous and to scholars of Late Antiquity.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Cicero*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
At the time of the conspiracy of Catiline the Saturnalia lasted only one day, December 19; in the time of Augustus three days were devoted to them (December 17‑19). See the note on <I>Sulla</I>, xviii.5.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: For more detailed information, see the article
		<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
